e synthesis","Activates dopamine receptors directly","Blocks dopamine reuptake into neurons","Stimulates dopamine release from neurons","Prevents breakdown of dopamine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMAO-B inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing dopamine breakdown\u003C/strong\u003E. By inhibiting the MAO-B enzyme, these drugs prevent dopamine metabolism in the presynaptic neuron, leading to increased dopamine in the presynaptic neuron that can then be released into the synaptic cleft.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this mechanism explains why the alternative answers are incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMAO-B inhibitors are selective for dopamine metabolism and have minimal effects on other monoamine neurotransmitters, making them particularly useful in Parkinson disease. This selectivity helps reduce side effects compared to non-selective MAO inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Monoamine oxidase type B (MAO-B) inhibitors work by blocking the breakdown of dopamine.","MAO-B inhibitors are selective for dopamine metabolism.","MAO-B inhibitors are used in Parkinson disease to increase dopamine availability."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62186"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16795"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62186"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T10:33:51+10:30","updatedAt":"20